[cows lowing]

25
00:02:35.545 --> 00:02:37.005
[brakes screech]

26
00:02:37.105 --> 00:02:38.766
[car doors shut]

27
00:02:38.866 --> 00:02:41.807
The things we lose
to keep you fed.

28
00:02:41.907 --> 00:02:44.008
[lowing]

29
00:02:44.108 --> 00:02:45.849
[police radio chatter]

30
00:02:45.949 --> 00:02:48.210
- Jesus. that's John Dutton.

31
00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:50.310
Commissioner. you all right?

32
00:02:53.391 --> 00:02:56.052
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33
00:02:56.152 --> 00:03:03.235
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34
00:03:55.414 --> 00:03:57.875
[indistinct chatter]

35
00:03:57.975 --> 00:04:01.996
<i>- The state of Montana</i>
<i>has never gauged its progress</i>

36
00:04:02.096 --> 00:04:04.957
<i>by the size of its cities.</i>

37
00:04:05.057 --> 00:04:06.878
<i>We measure our progress</i>

38
00:04:06.978 --> 00:04:09.239
<i>by how those cities</i>
<i>impact the people</i>

39
00:04:09.339 --> 00:04:11.400
<i>and the land surrounding them.</i>

40
00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:13.361
<i>the land that feeds them.</i>

41
00:04:13.461 --> 00:04:16.802
<i>provides their water.</i>
<i>nourishes their souls.</i>

42
00:04:16.902 --> 00:04:18.842
<i>- This doesn't sound like</i>
<i>a legal argument. Mr. Dutton.</i>

43
00:04:18.942 --> 00:04:20.803
<i>It sounds like a lecture.</i>

44
00:04:20.903 --> 00:04:22.844
<i>- Well. it's a summation</i>
<i>of our state constitution.</i>

45
00:04:22.944 --> 00:04:24.365
<i>which clearly states</i>
<i>that land preservation</i>

46
00:04:24.465 --> 00:04:26.365
and property rights
take precedence

47
00:04:26.465 --> 00:04:28.006
over public expansion.

48
00:04:28.106 --> 00:04:30.127
- The constitution
clearly denotes

49
00:04:30.227 --> 00:04:31.767
the state's right
to eminent domain

50
00:04:31.867 --> 00:04:33.488
and grants the authority
to condemn property

51
00:04:33.588 --> 00:04:35.128
for the public good.

52
00:04:35.228 --> 00:04:36.489
- For essential
public services

53
00:04:36.589 --> 00:04:38.770
like hospitals. schools.
highways--

54
00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:40.370
not housing developments.

55
00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:43.011
- Housing is essential.

56
00:04:43.111 --> 00:04:45.612
Bozeman has doubled
in size in a decade.

57
00:04:45.712 --> 00:04:47.573
We're 30 miles away.

58
00:04:47.673 --> 00:04:51.614
and our population is less
than it was 40 years ago.

59
00:04:51.714 --> 00:04:56.136
Why? Because their fence
guarantees we don't grow.

60
00:04:56.236 --> 00:04:57.737
Stagnation is death for a town.

61
00:04:57.837 --> 00:05:00.017
and the Duttons
are the ones killing it.

62
00:05:00.117 --> 00:05:02.738
- Well. poetic if it were true.

63
00:05:02.838 --> 00:05:05.259
since a Dutton
founded the town.

64
00:05:05.359 --> 00:05:07.580
As it stands.
the defendant is correct.

65
00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:10.381
Our land use laws
are quite clear.

66
00:05:10.481 --> 00:05:12.222
For this commission
to grant eminent domain.

67
00:05:12.322 --> 00:05:16.383
you must show
public need. not desire.

68
00:05:16.483 --> 00:05:18.104
- I think
that's enough posturing.

69
00:05:18.204 --> 00:05:19.745
Let's put it to a vote.
- The plaintiff hasn't shown

70
00:05:19.845 --> 00:05:21.465
any legal imperative
for a vote.

71
00:05:21.565 --> 00:05:23.426
so this case is dismissed.

72
00:05:23.526 --> 00:05:25.527
[gavel thuds]

73
00:05:28.448 --> 00:05:30.949
- It's 30.000 acres. Jamie.

74
00:05:31.049 --> 00:05:33.670
That isn't a fraction
of the ranch.

75
00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:37.151
Okay. look. you can harvest
the timber first.

76
00:05:37.251 --> 00:05:39.432
no environmental review.
nothing.

77
00:05:39.532 --> 00:05:42.713
You can cut every tree
to the root.

78
00:05:42.813 --> 00:05:44.394
- You want to suggest
to my father

79
00:05:44.494 --> 00:05:46.194
that he clear-cut his land.
be my guest.

80
00:05:46.294 --> 00:05:48.155
You're a braver man than me.

81
00:05:48.255 --> 00:05:50.596
- Just mention it. Jamie.

82
00:05:50.696 --> 00:05:52.597
The town grows. or it dies.

83
00:05:52.697 --> 00:05:54.957
- Well. maybe it
should grow...up.

84
00:05:55.057 --> 00:05:58.799
Condos. Alan. like
they have in San Francisco.

85
00:05:58.899 --> 00:06:01.280
- Condos?

86
00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:03.981
Who wants to live
in a condo in Montana?

87
00:06:16.545 --> 00:06:19.246
- I don't know how you're gonna
get 'em out by yourself.

88
00:06:19.346 --> 00:06:21.347
- Don't have to get 'em
all out.

89
00:06:22.387 --> 00:06:24.168
Just that stallion.

90
00:06:24.268 --> 00:06:26.769
Once he's gone. the rest
will leave on their own.

91
00:06:26.869 --> 00:06:29.490
- Best of luck. That bastard
kicked my truck door so hard.

92
00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:32.251
we had to use a crowbar
to get it open.

93
00:06:32.351 --> 00:06:34.772
That damn mustang's done more
in one week to stop drilling

94
00:06:34.872 --> 00:06:36.813
than every environmental
group in the state.

95
00:06:36.913 --> 00:06:39.474
- Maybe I should just leave him
where he is then.

96
00:06:42.515 --> 00:06:44.776
- Where'd you find this guy?

97
00:06:44.876 --> 00:06:46.816
- Yellow pages.

98
00:06:46.916 --> 00:06:48.977
Ad says he works
with problem horses.

99
00:06:49.077 --> 00:06:51.078
- Oh. this'll be interesting.

100
00:06:53.079 --> 00:06:55.079
- Kid's fucking crazy.

101
00:06:55.399 --> 00:06:57.400
[horse whinnies]

102
00:06:59.241 --> 00:07:01.742
- Yeah. uh...

103
00:07:01.842 --> 00:07:04.002
sure is building something.

104
00:07:05.963 --> 00:07:07.304
[knock on door]

105
00:07:07.404 --> 00:07:09.545
- [softly] Beth.
- Of course he didn't.

106
00:07:09.645 --> 00:07:11.505
He couldn't find his ass
with both hands.

107
00:07:11.605 --> 00:07:13.426
- Bob--Bob needs you.
- Give me a minute.

108
00:07:13.526 --> 00:07:16.467
- I don't think
he has a minute.

109
00:07:16.567 --> 00:07:18.148
- God damn it. Bob.
I didn't come here

110
00:07:18.248 --> 00:07:19.668
to do business
with these people.

111
00:07:19.768 --> 00:07:21.669
I came here to do
business with you.

112
00:07:21.769 --> 00:07:25.410
- I can hear you screaming
halfway down the hall. Craig.

113
00:07:30.772 --> 00:07:32.953
- I thought we were gonna try
and work this out. Bob.

114
00:07:33.053 --> 00:07:34.274
- We've been trying
to work this out

115
00:07:34.374 --> 00:07:37.075
for three hours. Craig.

116
00:07:37.175 --> 00:07:39.075
This is the alternative.

117
00:07:39.175 --> 00:07:40.476
- We don't want to merge.

118
00:07:40.576 --> 00:07:42.517
- No one wants
to merge with you.

119
00:07:42.617 --> 00:07:43.957
You have
a three-to-one debt ratio.

120
00:07:44.057 --> 00:07:46.838
It'd be easier to sell VCRs.

121
00:07:46.938 --> 00:07:51.400
- I'm not gonna be bullied
by your hatchet man. Bob.

122
00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:53.200
We will pull our funds.

123
00:07:53.300 --> 00:07:56.442
and we will take our business
down the street to Chase.

124
00:07:56.542 --> 00:07:58.482
- We're just asking you
to suspend the dividend.

125
00:07:58.582 --> 00:07:59.923
- And kill the stock!

126
00:08:00.023 --> 00:08:01.523
- What do you think's
gonna happen

127
00:08:01.623 --> 00:08:04.765
when I dump our 18% share
tomorrow morning?

128
00:08:04.865 --> 00:08:06.165
I'll tell you what.

129
00:08:06.265 --> 00:08:08.046
The stock will drop below 10.

130
00:08:08.146 --> 00:08:10.047
SEC will suspend trading.

131
00:08:10.147 --> 00:08:13.128
and every creditor you have
will file on you.

132
00:08:13.228 --> 00:08:16.209
Your company will be
chapter 11 by Friday.

133
00:08:16.309 --> 00:08:18.370
and since we're
your largest creditors.

134
00:08:18.470 --> 00:08:21.571
I can promise you there'll be
no negotiating then.

135
00:08:21.671 --> 00:08:25.052
I will be CEO of
IL Energy by Monday.

136
00:08:25.152 --> 00:08:27.293
I will fire every
fucking employee.

137
00:08:27.393 --> 00:08:30.294
Then I will sell your leases
and equipment to Chevron

138
00:08:30.394 --> 00:08:33.975
for 30¢ on the dollar.
and you. buddy.

139
00:08:34.075 --> 00:08:36.216
you will have
the unique distinction

140
00:08:36.316 --> 00:08:37.897
of being the only
drilling company

141
00:08:37.997 --> 00:08:40.177
to go bankrupt
in the largest oil boom

142
00:08:40.277 --> 00:08:42.658
of the last century.

143
00:08:42.758 --> 00:08:46.180
Won't that look good
on a resume?

144
00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:50.101
- I started this company
in my garage.

145
00:08:50.201 --> 00:08:51.702
- That's where
it's gonna end up

146
00:08:51.802 --> 00:08:53.022
if you don't suspend
the dividend

147
00:08:53.122 --> 00:08:55.763
and allow us
to assume management.

148
00:08:57.204 --> 00:08:59.184
Don't look at him.

149
00:08:59.284 --> 00:09:01.285
You're dealing with me now.

150
00:09:03.286 --> 00:09:05.707
So what's it gonna be?

151
00:09:05.807 --> 00:09:08.148
Are we restructuring
your company tomorrow

152
00:09:08.248 --> 00:09:10.248
or killing it?

153
00:09:15.450 --> 00:09:16.871
- Good.

154
00:09:16.971 --> 00:09:18.972
You made the right choice.
Craig.

155
00:09:23.453 --> 00:09:25.454
We'll get you through this.

156
00:09:29.495 --> 00:09:31.496
- [under breath] Bitch.

157
00:09:36.978 --> 00:09:39.239
- I just saved your house.

158
00:09:39.339 --> 00:09:41.680
I put your kids
through college.

159
00:09:41.780 --> 00:09:44.621
Maybe you should say
something more appropriate.

160
00:09:49.223 --> 00:09:51.223
- Thank you.

161
00:09:51.863 --> 00:09:53.864
- You're welcome.

162
00:09:59.306 --> 00:10:00.367
<i>[horse whinnies]</i>

163
00:10:00.467 --> 00:10:02.467
<i>[thump]</i>

164
00:10:03.628 --> 00:10:06.889
<i>[horse whinnying. thrashing]</i>

165
00:10:06.989 --> 00:10:08.370
<i>[muffled thumping]</i>

166
00:10:08.470 --> 00:10:10.290
<i>[horse whinnying]</i>

167
00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:12.971
<i>[thudding continues]</i>

168
00:10:13.071 --> 00:10:16.052
<i>[pop/folksy rap music]</i>

169
00:10:16.152 --> 00:10:22.295
<i>♪ ♪</i>

170
00:10:22.395 --> 00:10:25.696
<i>[rapping]</i>

171
00:10:25.796 --> 00:10:28.137
<i>[horse whinnies]</i>
<i>[thump]</i>

172
00:10:28.237 --> 00:10:30.978
<i>- ♪ Another suicide.</i>
<i>that's just the worst ♪</i>

173
00:10:31.078 --> 00:10:33.899
<i>[indistinct singing]</i>

174
00:10:33.999 --> 00:10:35.980
<i>♪ ♪</i>

175
00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:38.500
<i>[horse whinnies]</i>
<i>[thump]</i>

176
00:10:38.600 --> 00:10:40.741
<i>♪ And here's the kinda town ♪</i>

177
00:10:40.841 --> 00:10:44.663
<i>♪ Singing to the moon</i>
<i>our lonesome song ♪</i>

178
00:10:44.763 --> 00:10:48.984
<i>[horse continues</i>
<i>whinnying]</i>

179
00:10:49.084 --> 00:10:50.745
<i>[thump]</i>

180
00:10:50.845 --> 00:10:56.187
<i>[song continues]</i>
<i>[thumping continues]</i>

181
00:10:56.287 --> 00:10:58.428
[horse snorts]

182
00:10:58.528 --> 00:11:00.348
<i>[horse whinnying.</i>
<i>thrashing]</i>

183
00:11:00.448 --> 00:11:03.830
<i>[thumping. snorting]</i>

184
00:11:03.930 --> 00:11:06.111
[children playing]
<i>[thumping continues]</i>

185
00:11:06.211 --> 00:11:07.431
- Daddy!

186
00:11:07.531 --> 00:11:09.152
- Hey. buddy.

187
00:11:09.252 --> 00:11:11.572
<i>[horse continues thumping.</i>
<i>whinnying]</i>

188
00:11:13.293 --> 00:11:15.354
- Bet it was fun putting him
in the trailer.

189
00:11:15.454 --> 00:11:17.835
- Yeah. they call him
a tornado.

190
00:11:17.935 --> 00:11:20.236
- How are you planning
on getting him out?

191
00:11:20.336 --> 00:11:21.796
- I'm just making this up
as I go. babe.

192
00:11:21.896 --> 00:11:24.637
<i>[thumping. snorting</i>
<i>continues]</i>

193
00:11:24.737 --> 00:11:26.958
I'd step back a bit further
if I were you.

194
00:11:27.058 --> 00:11:30.599
[horse whinnying.
thumping]

195
00:11:30.699 --> 00:11:31.800
It's all right.

196
00:11:31.900 --> 00:11:33.280
[thud]

197
00:11:33.380 --> 00:11:35.081
I know it don't
seem like it. but it is.

198
00:11:35.181 --> 00:11:38.362
[thudding. whinnying]

199
00:11:38.462 --> 00:11:40.043
Easy.
[horse snorting]

200
00:11:40.143 --> 00:11:42.364
Easy.
[horse grunts]

201
00:11:42.464 --> 00:11:44.444
Whoa. whoa. whoa. whoa.

202
00:11:44.544 --> 00:11:46.725
Easy. easy.
That's it.

203
00:11:46.825 --> 00:11:48.826
That's it.

204
00:11:49.706 --> 00:11:51.707
Hey.
[horse grunting. snorting]

205
00:11:52.587 --> 00:11:54.208
Whoa...whoa.
[horse grunting]

206
00:11:54.308 --> 00:11:55.729
Whoa. whoa. whoa!

207
00:11:55.829 --> 00:11:57.649
You kids get back!

208
00:11:57.749 --> 00:11:59.090
Hey. hey. hey.

209
00:11:59.190 --> 00:12:00.930
[grunting]

210
00:12:01.030 --> 00:12:03.411
That's it. that's it.
Come on.

211
00:12:03.511 --> 00:12:04.892
[horse grunting. snorting]

212
00:12:04.992 --> 00:12:06.693
It's all right.
It's all right.

213
00:12:06.793 --> 00:12:08.793
[horse grunting softer]

214
00:12:12.275 --> 00:12:13.695
- Can I pet him?

215
00:12:13.795 --> 00:12:16.456
- Sure. son.
in about a year.

216
00:12:16.556 --> 00:12:19.457
- No fear in this one.
He got that from you.

217
00:12:19.557 --> 00:12:22.898
- You mean no common sense.
He got that from you.

218
00:12:22.998 --> 00:12:27.720
- Well. I suppose your homework
is in the kitchen doing itself.

219
00:12:29.681 --> 00:12:31.181
[kids chattering.
giggling]

220
00:12:31.281 --> 00:12:32.542
[loud grunting]

221
00:12:32.642 --> 00:12:35.363
Oh. he's gonna be fun to break.

222
00:12:36.843 --> 00:12:39.564
Well. holler at me
if you need my help.

223
00:12:41.005 --> 00:12:42.426
- Free tomorrow?

224
00:12:42.526 --> 00:12:44.146
Could use a hand.

225
00:12:44.246 --> 00:12:46.147
- Yeah. sure.

226
00:12:46.247 --> 00:12:48.428
- Bring a horse.

227
00:12:48.528 --> 00:12:50.528
Just not that one.

228
00:12:55.810 --> 00:12:58.791
- Wow. My brother
actually talked to me.

229
00:12:58.891 --> 00:13:01.352
Well. that was progress.

230
00:13:01.452 --> 00:13:03.593
- Yeah. it was something.

231
00:13:03.693 --> 00:13:05.474
- I got parent conferences
tonight.

232
00:13:05.574 --> 00:13:07.395
so you're on Tate patrol.

233
00:13:07.495 --> 00:13:09.495
- All right.

234
00:13:11.496 --> 00:13:13.497
- I wonder what he's thinking.

235
00:13:14.137 --> 00:13:16.998
- Well. he's probably thinking
I took his freedom.

236
00:13:17.098 --> 00:13:18.879
- Well. he's right.

237
00:13:18.979 --> 00:13:21.200
[horse snuffling softly]

238
00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:23.300
Supper's ready.

239
00:13:37.385 --> 00:13:39.386
- Ah. damn it.

240
00:13:40.987 --> 00:13:44.388
Your mother was always
better at this.

241
00:13:45.789 --> 00:13:47.789
- Hey. you know
who's really good at it?

242
00:13:49.310 --> 00:13:51.451
Doctors.
- Yeah.

243
00:13:51.551 --> 00:13:53.811
- Should have done
that yesterday.

244
00:13:53.911 --> 00:13:56.472
Here. let me do it.
Let me do it.

245
00:13:58.393 --> 00:14:01.414
All right. Alan asked me
to mention it. so I will.

246
00:14:01.514 --> 00:14:03.935
They'd allow us to harvest
the timber before the--

247
00:14:04.035 --> 00:14:06.036
- No.

248
00:14:06.636 --> 00:14:08.777
The answer's no.
- Yeah.

249
00:14:08.877 --> 00:14:11.098
Can I do this?

250
00:14:11.198 --> 00:14:13.138
- Yeah.

251
00:14:13.238 --> 00:14:16.420
When you say no. it must be
the death of the question.

252
00:14:16.520 --> 00:14:17.700
- Mm-hmm. I understand.

253
00:14:17.800 --> 00:14:19.141
- If there's even a hint
of maybe.

254
00:14:19.241 --> 00:14:20.461
the questions won't stop
until they find

255
00:14:20.561 --> 00:14:22.142
something you can't say no to.

256
00:14:22.242 --> 00:14:24.242
- Mm.

257
00:14:28.044 --> 00:14:29.104
- You got to learn
when to think

258
00:14:29.204 --> 00:14:30.545
like a lawyer.
you understand?

259
00:14:30.645 --> 00:14:32.786
And when to think
like a landowner.

260
00:14:32.886 --> 00:14:34.886
Or a lawyer's
all you're ever gonna be.

261
00:14:37.967 --> 00:14:39.508
Yeah.

262
00:14:39.608 --> 00:14:42.509
Well. I'll say this.
You...

263
00:14:42.609 --> 00:14:44.610
You got your mother's hands.

264
00:14:47.011 --> 00:14:48.351
[barking]

265
00:14:48.451 --> 00:14:51.312
[helicopter blades whirring]

266
00:14:51.412 --> 00:14:54.954
[horses whinnying]

267
00:14:55.054 --> 00:14:56.314
- Hey.

268
00:14:56.414 --> 00:14:58.415
I told them no.

269
00:15:04.097 --> 00:15:06.098
Hey. I said
you wouldn't consider it.

270
00:15:07.458 --> 00:15:09.579
Should you consider it?
Absolutely.

271
00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:14.601
We could use the money and the
leverage that comes with it.

272
00:15:14.701 --> 00:15:16.702
- You're not coming. Dad?

273
00:15:18.582 --> 00:15:20.583
- No. I got a meeting
in Bozeman.

274
00:15:22.864 --> 00:15:25.245
Why don't you take
your badge out with you today?

275
00:15:25.345 --> 00:15:27.045
Take a rifle too.

276
00:15:27.145 --> 00:15:29.126
- I mean. they won't give us
any trouble over strays.

277
00:15:29.226 --> 00:15:31.087
I mean. hell. they'll probably
help us round them up.

278
00:15:31.187 --> 00:15:33.888
- Well. the badge is for
the ranchers riding with you.

279
00:15:33.988 --> 00:15:35.989
It'll keep them from
bringing home any extras.

280
00:15:39.150 --> 00:15:40.690
- Did you hear me?

281
00:15:40.790 --> 00:15:44.552
[helicopter engine
powering up thrum]

282
00:15:46.072 --> 00:15:48.853
- Leverage is knowing
if someone had...

283
00:15:48.953 --> 00:15:50.954
all the money in the world...

284
00:15:52.915 --> 00:15:55.576
This is what they'd buy.

285
00:15:55.676 --> 00:15:58.577
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

286
00:15:58.677 --> 00:16:05.599
<i>♪ ♪</i>

287
00:16:19.204 --> 00:16:22.686
<i>[intense music build-up]</i>

288
00:16:27.327 --> 00:16:30.228
<i>[soft. dramatic music]</i>

289
00:16:30.328 --> 00:16:35.470
<i>♪ ♪</i>

290
00:16:35.570 --> 00:16:37.911
[bird of prey cries]

291
00:16:38.011 --> 00:16:40.552
<i>[distant chanting]</i>

292
00:16:40.652 --> 00:16:43.433
[chanting in native language]

293
00:16:43.533 --> 00:16:45.914
♪ ♪

294
00:16:46.014 --> 00:16:49.195
[drumming intensifies]

295
00:16:49.295 --> 00:16:52.276
[chanting]

296
00:16:52.376 --> 00:16:58.298
♪ ♪

297
00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:05.561
[chanting. drumming continue]

298
00:17:05.661 --> 00:17:07.402
[knocking at door]

299
00:17:07.502 --> 00:17:10.423
<i>[chanting and drumming</i>
<i>continues in background]</i>

300
00:17:14.104 --> 00:17:15.965
- Senator.

301
00:17:16.065 --> 00:17:17.606
- I'm sorry I'm late.

302
00:17:17.706 --> 00:17:19.566
I wanted to see
the reservation first.

303
00:17:19.666 --> 00:17:21.407
- Did you enjoy your tour?

304
00:17:21.507 --> 00:17:23.648
- No. no. I did not.

305
00:17:23.748 --> 00:17:25.969
- Well. it's good
that you took it.

306
00:17:26.069 --> 00:17:28.810
Inequity must be witnessed
to be changed.

307
00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:30.570
Please have a seat.

308
00:17:30.670 --> 00:17:32.671
- Oh.

309
00:17:34.031 --> 00:17:35.852
I can't imagine all
your mother overcame

310
00:17:35.952 --> 00:17:37.533
just to raise you here.

311
00:17:37.633 --> 00:17:40.934
- I never met my mother.
and I wasn't raised here.

312
00:17:41.034 --> 00:17:43.495
Till I was 18.
I thought I was Mexican

313
00:17:43.595 --> 00:17:45.616
even though
I didn't look Mexican

314
00:17:45.716 --> 00:17:47.336
and I didn't feel Mexican.

315
00:17:47.436 --> 00:17:50.658
if one can feel their heritage.
which I believe one can.

316
00:17:50.758 --> 00:17:54.499
When I turned 18. my adoption
records were unsealed.

317
00:17:54.599 --> 00:17:56.820
and imagine my surprise.

318
00:17:56.920 --> 00:17:59.021
I confronted
my adopted parents.

319
00:17:59.121 --> 00:18:02.202
who said they lied
to protect me.

320
00:18:04.122 --> 00:18:06.503
They said as a Mexican.

321
00:18:06.603 --> 00:18:10.345
I would face
discrimination. sure.

322
00:18:10.445 --> 00:18:14.106
but as an Indian.
I would know a hatred

323
00:18:14.206 --> 00:18:17.627
that had to be endured
to be fully understood.

324
00:18:17.727 --> 00:18:21.309
They thought they were giving
me a better chance at life.

325
00:18:21.409 --> 00:18:26.751
That's this nation's policy
toward us. always has been.

326
00:18:26.851 --> 00:18:29.552
If we want a better life.
all we have to do

327
00:18:29.652 --> 00:18:31.712
is stop being Indian.

328
00:18:31.812 --> 00:18:34.113
- I'm gonna change that policy.

329
00:18:34.213 --> 00:18:37.535
- My people are the only ones
that can change that policy.

330
00:18:39.535 --> 00:18:41.676
[sighs]

331
00:18:41.776 --> 00:18:43.717
The gambler's money
is like a river.

332
00:18:43.817 --> 00:18:48.038
flowing one way...
our way.

333
00:18:48.138 --> 00:18:50.599
Senator. you've
never driven a road

334
00:18:50.699 --> 00:18:53.921
or walked a trail
or skied a mountain in Montana

335
00:18:54.021 --> 00:18:56.682
that didn't belong
to my people first.

336
00:18:56.782 --> 00:19:00.243
This nation doesn't
want to give it back?

337
00:19:00.343 --> 00:19:01.963
So be it.

338
00:19:02.063 --> 00:19:04.804
We'll buy it back...

339
00:19:04.904 --> 00:19:06.565
with their money.

340
00:19:06.665 --> 00:19:08.666
- So what do you want from me?

341
00:19:10.867 --> 00:19:12.867
- I want you to help me
spend it.

342
00:19:14.388 --> 00:19:17.429
Come. Meet the people
we're saving.

343
00:19:20.470 --> 00:19:23.971
- Ladies and gentlemen.
let's welcome the new chairman

344
00:19:24.071 --> 00:19:28.013
of Broken Rock.
Thomas Rainwater!

345
00:19:28.113 --> 00:19:30.914
[cheers and applause]

346
00:19:35.115 --> 00:19:36.936
- What about water and power?

347
00:19:37.036 --> 00:19:39.257
You don't need
a permit for that?

348
00:19:39.357 --> 00:19:42.178
See. the bank's concern is
that you're gonna break ground.

349
00:19:42.278 --> 00:19:45.459
and the state or the fucking
EPA paper us in lawsuits

350
00:19:45.559 --> 00:19:48.780
because we built a power plant
without a permit.

351
00:19:48.880 --> 00:19:50.941
- In the state of Montana.
no permit is required

352
00:19:51.041 --> 00:19:53.942
to build a power source
for a mine or a mill.

353
00:19:54.042 --> 00:19:56.063
Now. we'll construct
our own mill

354
00:19:56.163 --> 00:19:58.024
that will also allow us
to harvest wood

355
00:19:58.124 --> 00:20:00.905
directly from the forest.

356
00:20:01.005 --> 00:20:03.846
cutting our lumber cost by 65%.

357
00:20:06.527 --> 00:20:09.428
Damming the river here
will generate enough power

358
00:20:09.528 --> 00:20:11.309
to light every home
in the subdivision.

359
00:20:11.409 --> 00:20:14.350
Now. this is a self-sustaining
community

360
00:20:14.450 --> 00:20:19.352
30 miles from the most pristine
wilderness in North America.

361
00:20:19.452 --> 00:20:21.592
Now. if you don't see
the potential in that.

362
00:20:21.692 --> 00:20:24.113
we need another bank.
- We see the potential.

363
00:20:24.213 --> 00:20:26.474
I just--

364
00:20:26.574 --> 00:20:29.475
There are no restrictions
on damming a river?

365
00:20:29.575 --> 00:20:31.636
- Beavers do it
all the time.

366
00:20:31.736 --> 00:20:34.197
On our land it's our river.

367
00:20:34.297 --> 00:20:36.438
Now. this isn't California.
gentlemen.

368
00:20:36.538 --> 00:20:38.539
This is Montana.

369
00:20:41.700 --> 00:20:43.900
We can do whatever we want.

370
00:20:44.941 --> 00:20:48.842
[traffic noises]

371
00:20:48.942 --> 00:20:51.843
<i>[soft rock playing]</i>

372
00:20:51.943 --> 00:20:58.746
<i>♪ ♪</i>

373
00:21:11.671 --> 00:21:14.592
- My name's Ted.
Where are you from?

374
00:21:16.112 --> 00:21:17.693
Really?
[laughs]

375
00:21:17.793 --> 00:21:19.533
I've been here a week.

376
00:21:19.633 --> 00:21:22.455
You're the first person I've
met who's actually from here.

377
00:21:22.555 --> 00:21:24.615
Can I buy you another drink?

378
00:21:24.715 --> 00:21:26.716
- Why not?

379
00:21:27.276 --> 00:21:29.657
Hey. Dalton.
give me another one.

380
00:21:29.757 --> 00:21:31.838
- You don't live here anymore.
though. not dressed like that.

381
00:21:32.838 --> 00:21:35.699
You came back
for a family reunion.

382
00:21:35.799 --> 00:21:39.461
No. no. those never happen
at home for some reason.

383
00:21:39.561 --> 00:21:43.742
Let's see. Bozeman
is a college town.

384
00:21:43.842 --> 00:21:47.344
so I'm gonna say
a school reunion.

385
00:21:47.444 --> 00:21:50.845
class of...2006.

386
00:21:52.405 --> 00:21:54.906
Am I close?

387
00:21:55.006 --> 00:21:57.587
- Do you feel close. Ted?

388
00:21:57.687 --> 00:21:59.948
- Ah. it feels like
I'm getting close.

389
00:22:00.048 --> 00:22:02.049
- My turn.

390
00:22:03.249 --> 00:22:04.550
You're in real estate
or something

391
00:22:04.650 --> 00:22:06.591
equally as unimportant.
married.

392
00:22:06.691 --> 00:22:08.271
couple of kids. one on the way.

393
00:22:08.371 --> 00:22:10.832
That was your excuse
to come out here.

394
00:22:10.932 --> 00:22:12.953
Need the break.
Work. family life.

395
00:22:13.053 --> 00:22:14.633
It's so demanding.

396
00:22:14.733 --> 00:22:18.075
A little fresh air.
a little "me time."

397
00:22:18.175 --> 00:22:20.276
You came alone 'cause none of
your friends could afford it.

398
00:22:20.376 --> 00:22:22.076
and those who do.
they--they have wives

399
00:22:22.176 --> 00:22:23.757
a lot smarter than yours
'cause let's be honest. Ted.

400
00:22:23.857 --> 00:22:26.118
you didn't come here to fish.

401
00:22:26.218 --> 00:22:27.798
You're hunting.

402
00:22:27.898 --> 00:22:28.839
That's why
you're sitting in a bar

403
00:22:28.939 --> 00:22:31.259
instead of standing in a river.

404
00:22:32.460 --> 00:22:34.041
- Who the hell are you
to judge me?

405
00:22:34.141 --> 00:22:35.881
- I ain't judging you. buddy.

406
00:22:35.981 --> 00:22:37.442
- Morning. gentlemen.

407
00:22:37.542 --> 00:22:41.523
- I'm hunting too.
just not hunting you.

408
00:22:41.623 --> 00:22:43.624
- What's wrong with me?

409
00:22:44.544 --> 00:22:47.846
- You look like
a real soft fuck. Ted.

410
00:22:47.946 --> 00:22:50.066
All you city boys do.

411
00:22:54.988 --> 00:22:57.489
Gentlemen.
mind if I join you?

412
00:22:57.589 --> 00:22:59.570
[men shouting]

413
00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:01.671
- They even got
the barb wire tore down.

414
00:23:02.831 --> 00:23:04.772
That is our property.
god damn it.

415
00:23:04.872 --> 00:23:08.093
- Can't hear ya.
Come about 2 feet closer.

416
00:23:08.193 --> 00:23:10.454
- You think I won't?
- I think you shouldn't.

417
00:23:10.554 --> 00:23:13.295
but coming on our land
is bred into you people.

418
00:23:13.395 --> 00:23:15.396
- I've had enough of your shit.

419
00:23:16.756 --> 00:23:18.457
Let me tell you something--

420
00:23:18.557 --> 00:23:21.178
[men shouting]

421
00:23:21.278 --> 00:23:22.698
- When those cattle
walked onto our land.

422
00:23:22.798 --> 00:23:25.659
they became our cattle
to do as we please.

423
00:23:25.759 --> 00:23:28.660
- Whatever happens next
happens to you first.

424
00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:31.461
[helicopter whirring]

425
00:23:31.561 --> 00:23:32.902
<i>[tense music]</i>

426
00:23:33.002 --> 00:23:34.462
- Son of a bitch.

427
00:23:34.562 --> 00:23:38.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

428
00:23:38.644 --> 00:23:39.904
- Back up.

429
00:23:40.004 --> 00:23:42.005
- You should respect
your veterans.

430
00:24:00.892 --> 00:24:02.793
- Boy. you sure made
a mess of this.

431
00:24:02.893 --> 00:24:04.893
- It was a mess
when I got here.

432
00:24:05.574 --> 00:24:07.154
- This is a tribal issue. John.

433
00:24:07.254 --> 00:24:09.035
Livestock commission's
got no authority here.

434
00:24:09.135 --> 00:24:11.136
- Those look like livestock
to me.

435
00:24:12.336 --> 00:24:15.857
- The Chief's at Commencement.
but I'm calling the shots.

436
00:24:17.738 --> 00:24:20.259
- I'm impressed you said that
with a straight face. Ben.

437
00:24:25.141 --> 00:24:27.922
- Cattle wandered
onto res land. John.

438
00:24:28.022 --> 00:24:29.643
- Yeah. well.

439
00:24:29.743 --> 00:24:30.763
cattle don't know
the difference

440
00:24:30.863 --> 00:24:32.364
between your land and ours.

441
00:24:32.464 --> 00:24:34.044
- Neither did we
till the government

442
00:24:34.144 --> 00:24:35.725
showed us.
Ha.

443
00:24:35.825 --> 00:24:37.865
Now I guess we're showing you.

444
00:24:39.506 --> 00:24:42.787
I argued against it.
but the new chief...

445
00:24:44.428 --> 00:24:46.369
Hungry for a fight. this one.

446
00:24:46.469 --> 00:24:48.469
- God damn it. I just--

447
00:24:50.310 --> 00:24:53.211
I just don't see how anyone
gains from all this. Felix.

448
00:24:53.311 --> 00:24:56.472
- I don't either.
but he don't think like me.

449
00:24:57.633 --> 00:24:59.453
Grew up in Denver.

450
00:24:59.553 --> 00:25:02.895
went to some big university.

451
00:25:02.995 --> 00:25:04.995
Now he thinks like you.

452
00:25:14.639 --> 00:25:17.000
I'll keep 'em here
as long as I can. John.

453
00:25:20.641 --> 00:25:22.802
- I'll bring up hay
so they don't wander.

454
00:25:26.763 --> 00:25:28.764
Lee!
- I got to go.

455
00:25:30.285 --> 00:25:32.285
- Clear everyone out.

456
00:25:33.926 --> 00:25:36.367
- You know. there was barbed
wire on this fence a week ago.

457
00:25:39.448 --> 00:25:41.429
- I know.
Now clear them out.

458
00:25:41.529 --> 00:25:44.430
- Move out!
All right. let's go!

459
00:25:44.530 --> 00:25:48.151
<i>- ♪ Our flag was still there ♪</i>

460
00:25:48.251 --> 00:25:53.753
♪ Oh. say does that
star-spangled ♪

461
00:25:53.853 --> 00:25:59.715
♪ Banner yet wave ♪

462
00:25:59.815 --> 00:26:06.158
♪ O'er the land of the free ♪

463
00:26:06.258 --> 00:26:12.640
♪ And the home
of the brave ♪

464
00:26:12.740 --> 00:26:15.541
[cheers and applause]

465
00:26:19.102 --> 00:26:20.723
- Ladies and gentlemen.
I'd like to welcome you out

466
00:26:20.823 --> 00:26:22.444
to the 2018

467
00:26:22.544 --> 00:26:24.524
Greater Montana
Livestock Auction.

468
00:26:24.624 --> 00:26:26.125
We're gonna start out
with lot number one.

469
00:26:26.225 --> 00:26:29.206
It's Royal M. Duke.
a 2013 registered

470
00:26:29.306 --> 00:26:32.047
English bull offered
by Double G Angus Ranch.

471
00:26:32.147 --> 00:26:36.409
sired by Supreme Domino
out of Miss Domino.

472
00:26:36.509 --> 00:26:38.049
Now we're gonna start
the bidding out at 25.000.

473
00:26:38.149 --> 00:26:41.370
I'm at 25. I'm at 50.
[auctioneering]

474
00:26:41.470 --> 00:26:42.891
I'm at 55. gonna go 60.
at 60 now.

475
00:26:42.991 --> 00:26:45.772
now 5 on 65.000.
65 looking for 70.

476
00:26:45.872 --> 00:26:47.653
[auctioneering] 75. 75

477
00:26:47.753 --> 00:26:49.293
and now bid
at 80. 80.000. 85?

478
00:26:49.393 --> 00:26:50.854
85. now 90. 90?

479
00:26:50.954 --> 00:26:53.155
- One phone call.
I'll be right back.

480
00:26:55.636 --> 00:26:59.937
- We have any little recourse
on the Reservation land?

481
00:27:00.037 --> 00:27:02.658
- Civil maybe. but if
you're talking prosecution.

482
00:27:02.758 --> 00:27:04.759
we need friends in
the U.S. Attorney's Office.

483
00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:09.140
- Make some.

484
00:27:09.240 --> 00:27:10.821
[applause]

485
00:27:10.921 --> 00:27:12.342
Hello. Trent.

486
00:27:12.442 --> 00:27:14.502
- John.

487
00:27:14.602 --> 00:27:17.464
I wouldn't wish the week you're
having on my mother-in-law.

488
00:27:17.564 --> 00:27:20.044
[laughing]
- Well. it's only Tuesday.

489
00:27:21.605 --> 00:27:22.545
- 50. 60. 60.

490
00:27:22.645 --> 00:27:23.746
Now 70. 70 now.

491
00:27:23.846 --> 00:27:25.546
75. now bid at 80. 80.

492
00:27:25.646 --> 00:27:27.647
- John.

493
00:27:28.808 --> 00:27:30.228
- This is not the day. Dirk.

494
00:27:30.328 --> 00:27:31.749
- The word has it
you're hiring.

495
00:27:31.849 --> 00:27:34.610
- Cowboys. not criminals.

496
00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:37.351
- I can't stop him.

497
00:27:37.451 --> 00:27:39.451
You can.

498
00:27:39.892 --> 00:27:42.873
Jimmy's the only family
I have left.

499
00:27:42.973 --> 00:27:45.414
The favor's to me.
not to him.

500
00:27:46.614 --> 00:27:48.615
Please.

501
00:27:50.455 --> 00:27:52.456
Please.

502
00:27:55.977 --> 00:27:57.558
- We're gonna do this my way.
all right?

503
00:27:57.658 --> 00:27:59.799
You understand? My way.
- Yeah.

504
00:27:59.899 --> 00:28:02.080
I remember when your way
was the only way.

505
00:28:02.180 --> 00:28:04.180
and the world
was better for that.

506
00:28:05.941 --> 00:28:06.921
- Hello. Governor.
- John.

507
00:28:07.021 --> 00:28:09.042
How are you?

508
00:28:09.142 --> 00:28:11.143
Thank you.

509
00:28:12.183 --> 00:28:13.964
Jamie did well
at the hearing.

510
00:28:14.064 --> 00:28:16.205
- It's easy to do well
when the outcome's decided.

511
00:28:16.305 --> 00:28:17.925
- I couldn't hit it
if he didn't tee it up.

512
00:28:18.025 --> 00:28:20.006
and my offer
still stands. John.

513
00:28:20.106 --> 00:28:21.607
- Yeah. well...

514
00:28:21.707 --> 00:28:24.248
I don't want him in politics.

515
00:28:24.348 --> 00:28:26.008
- He's already in politics.

516
00:28:26.108 --> 00:28:28.769
- Yeah. with
a constituency of one.

517
00:28:28.869 --> 00:28:30.870
- [laughs]

518
00:28:32.311 --> 00:28:34.872
How concerned should I be
about this issue on the Res?

519
00:28:36.552 --> 00:28:39.173
- It's a new chief
showing off for his voters.

520
00:28:39.273 --> 00:28:41.274
We've all done it.

521
00:28:43.755 --> 00:28:46.976
[applause]
- Well...

522
00:28:47.076 --> 00:28:49.077
we should schedule
a lunch.

523
00:28:51.198 --> 00:28:53.018
- I could use a lunch.

524
00:28:53.118 --> 00:28:56.800
[background chatter]

525
00:28:59.721 --> 00:29:02.502
<i>[solemn music]</i>

526
00:29:02.602 --> 00:29:09.484
<i>♪ ♪</i>

527
00:29:11.205 --> 00:29:13.186
- Sold it to you. 135.
Sold it. 135.

528
00:29:13.286 --> 00:29:15.286
[indistinct chatter]
[cattle lowing]

529
00:29:19.448 --> 00:29:21.449
[distant howling]

530
00:29:30.652 --> 00:29:31.832
- You were right.

531
00:29:31.932 --> 00:29:33.933
They're building a city.

532
00:29:34.733 --> 00:29:37.114
Goodnight. Daddy.

533
00:29:37.214 --> 00:29:40.435
- Goodnight. sweetheart.
Good to have you home.

534
00:29:40.535 --> 00:29:43.437
<i>[pensive string music]</i>

535
00:29:43.537 --> 00:29:50.339
<i>♪ ♪</i>

536
00:30:16.068 --> 00:30:18.329
- [clicking lips]

537
00:30:18.429 --> 00:30:21.410
[clicking tongue]

538
00:30:21.510 --> 00:30:23.651
That's it.

539
00:30:23.751 --> 00:30:26.352
Come on. That's it.

540
00:30:31.354 --> 00:30:34.895
That's it.
That's it. buddy.

541
00:30:34.995 --> 00:30:36.996
- Got tiger stripes
on his legs.

542
00:30:38.837 --> 00:30:40.777
You know what that means.
don't you?

543
00:30:40.877 --> 00:30:42.938
- [exhales sharply]

544
00:30:43.038 --> 00:30:45.279
Spanish blood.
- Pure.

545
00:30:46.439 --> 00:30:48.660
One of his ancestors
probably bucked a conquistador

546
00:30:48.760 --> 00:30:51.421
and took to the hills.

547
00:30:51.521 --> 00:30:52.902
You manage to break his spirit.

548
00:30:53.002 --> 00:30:55.063
no horse will
serve you better.

549
00:30:55.163 --> 00:30:57.664
- He'll serve me just fine
with spirit intact.

550
00:30:57.764 --> 00:30:59.464
- Yeah.

551
00:30:59.564 --> 00:31:01.845
I used to think
the same thing at your age.

552
00:31:03.206 --> 00:31:05.206
Hope you prove me wrong.

553
00:31:06.967 --> 00:31:08.948
- I didn't know them
were your cattle.

554
00:31:09.048 --> 00:31:11.048
- Would it have made
a difference?

555
00:31:15.490 --> 00:31:17.991
You don't want to be
on the wrong side of this. son.

556
00:31:18.091 --> 00:31:20.272
- Yeah. well. the list of
things I don't want is endless.

557
00:31:20.372 --> 00:31:21.912
You telling me what to do
is one of them.

558
00:31:22.012 --> 00:31:23.433
- I'm not telling you
what to do.

559
00:31:23.533 --> 00:31:25.354
I just don't want you
to get in trouble.

560
00:31:25.454 --> 00:31:27.594
- Well. if I'd have known
there was sides.

561
00:31:27.694 --> 00:31:29.695
I wouldn't have been
there at all.

562
00:31:33.577 --> 00:31:37.258
- Good lord. even here
the world just keeps on coming.

563
00:31:38.778 --> 00:31:40.719
- Rough week. huh?

564
00:31:40.819 --> 00:31:43.000
- Yeah.

565
00:31:43.100 --> 00:31:45.201
One only a grandson
could fix.

566
00:31:45.301 --> 00:31:47.122
Thought I'd come see

567
00:31:47.222 --> 00:31:49.902
Tate play in the dirt.
maybe even join him.

568
00:31:53.784 --> 00:31:56.325
- He's at Monica's parents.

569
00:31:56.425 --> 00:31:59.786
- I guess the early grandpa
gets the worm. huh?

570
00:32:08.149 --> 00:32:10.150
Can I give you
some advice. Kayce?

571
00:32:11.870 --> 00:32:13.871
Someday your son's
gonna test you.

572
00:32:15.552 --> 00:32:16.812
He's gonna force you
to make a decision

573
00:32:16.912 --> 00:32:18.853
that not only determines
his future

574
00:32:18.953 --> 00:32:21.414
but your place in it.

575
00:32:21.514 --> 00:32:23.655
I want you to remember me
standing here. son.

576
00:32:23.755 --> 00:32:27.056
before you make that decision.
because this--

577
00:32:27.156 --> 00:32:29.517
this is a consequence
of choosing wrong.

578
00:32:33.878 --> 00:32:35.939
- Anything else?

579
00:32:36.039 --> 00:32:38.040
- I just want to
know him. Kayce.

580
00:32:39.761 --> 00:32:42.662
- You know him.
- No. I don't. I don't.

581
00:32:42.762 --> 00:32:44.662
We've met.
but I don't really know him.

582
00:32:44.762 --> 00:32:46.763
And he doesn't know me.

583
00:32:49.564 --> 00:32:53.025
Is it too much to ask that you
help make that happen?

584
00:32:53.125 --> 00:32:55.586
- [humorless chuckle]

585
00:32:55.686 --> 00:32:58.687
You've always asked too much.

586
00:33:11.652 --> 00:33:13.873
[clicking tongue]

587
00:33:13.973 --> 00:33:15.974
[truck starts]

588
00:33:24.937 --> 00:33:26.938
- What was he doing here?

589
00:33:27.658 --> 00:33:29.479
- [sighs] Who knows?

590
00:33:29.579 --> 00:33:30.719
- Dad!

591
00:33:30.819 --> 00:33:32.820
Is this for me?

592
00:33:44.424 --> 00:33:47.325
<i>[hard rock music playing]</i>

593
00:33:47.425 --> 00:33:54.188
<i>♪ ♪</i>

594
00:34:05.752 --> 00:34:07.753
<i>[music stops]</i>

595
00:34:10.113 --> 00:34:12.114
- You Jimmy?

596
00:34:12.954 --> 00:34:14.955
Dirk Hurdstram's boy?

597
00:34:16.476 --> 00:34:17.776
- [stammers]

598
00:34:17.876 --> 00:34:20.257
- You alone. Jimmy?

599
00:34:20.357 --> 00:34:22.098
I'll take that as a yes.

600
00:34:22.198 --> 00:34:24.199
[Taser zapping]

601
00:34:32.282 --> 00:34:34.862
You're a two-time loser.
Jimmy.

602
00:34:34.962 --> 00:34:38.004
One more felony.
and they throw away the keys.

603
00:34:39.604 --> 00:34:41.605
You know what? You might
do all right in prison.

604
00:34:42.925 --> 00:34:44.466
You got the lips for it.

605
00:34:44.566 --> 00:34:46.587
- You're either a servant
or a king in this place.

606
00:34:46.687 --> 00:34:48.868
and I ain't no fucking servant.

607
00:34:48.968 --> 00:34:50.968
- No. no.

608
00:34:54.930 --> 00:34:57.271
You're a thief.

609
00:34:57.371 --> 00:34:58.791
- Oh. what the fuck. man?

610
00:34:58.891 --> 00:35:00.712
What the fuck. man?

611
00:35:00.812 --> 00:35:02.072
Wait. wait. wait!

612
00:35:02.172 --> 00:35:04.593
Wait. wait. wait!
Wait. wait!

613
00:35:04.693 --> 00:35:06.474
Fucking psycho. wait!

614
00:35:06.574 --> 00:35:08.835
- Jimmy. I'm gonna give
you two choices.

615
00:35:08.935 --> 00:35:11.276
One is I take you
and all this shit.

616
00:35:11.376 --> 00:35:13.316
and I drive you down
to the sheriff's office.

617
00:35:13.416 --> 00:35:15.997
and it's good riddance
to your sorry ass.

618
00:35:16.097 --> 00:35:18.558
or you prove that you
deserve another chance.

619
00:35:18.658 --> 00:35:22.560
From what I can see. you don't.
but it ain't up to me.

620
00:35:22.660 --> 00:35:25.041
- You're with the Yellowstone?

621
00:35:25.141 --> 00:35:27.121
- It's getting cold. Jimmy.

622
00:35:27.221 --> 00:35:29.442
You know what? Fuck it. I'm
taking you to the sheriff's.

623
00:35:29.542 --> 00:35:31.543
- Wait. just--
- Just get up.

624
00:35:34.104 --> 00:35:36.085
- Why would John Dutton
give a shit about me?

625
00:35:36.185 --> 00:35:38.185
- He doesn't.

626
00:35:40.306 --> 00:35:42.307
But he will.

627
00:35:44.428 --> 00:35:47.809
Now. you be a man about it.
Don't scream.

628
00:35:47.909 --> 00:35:51.210
- [breathing hard]

629
00:35:51.310 --> 00:35:54.111
[branding iron sizzles]
- [groaning]

630
00:36:00.914 --> 00:36:02.914
[groans]

631
00:36:06.236 --> 00:36:08.236
- You know where the ranch is?

632
00:36:10.357 --> 00:36:12.358
You start Monday.

633
00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:21.041
- Hey. we need
a new dishwasher.

634
00:36:22.922 --> 00:36:25.823
- I notice you never ask for
appliances with your pants on.

635
00:36:25.923 --> 00:36:28.064
- Number one. I make more money

636
00:36:28.164 --> 00:36:30.024
than you do. cowboy.
- Oh. yeah?

637
00:36:30.124 --> 00:36:31.865
- And number two.
I already bought it.

638
00:36:31.965 --> 00:36:33.426
No pants is so you don't bitch

639
00:36:33.526 --> 00:36:36.467
about driving to Billings
to pick it up.

640
00:36:36.567 --> 00:36:39.048
- Ugh. Billings.

641
00:36:40.328 --> 00:36:42.329
- It's so far.

642
00:36:45.570 --> 00:36:47.571
Tell me about today.

643
00:36:54.373 --> 00:36:56.454
- He just wants to know
his grandson.

644
00:36:58.575 --> 00:37:00.575
I guess we could give him that.
What do you think?

645
00:37:01.576 --> 00:37:04.117
- You know what I think.

646
00:37:04.217 --> 00:37:07.918
But we'll give it
to him anyway.

647
00:37:08.018 --> 00:37:10.019
It'll happen to us too
someday.

648
00:37:11.539 --> 00:37:15.161
Tate'll move away
and have a family of his own.

649
00:37:15.261 --> 00:37:18.062
and all we'll get
is little fixes.

650
00:37:20.743 --> 00:37:23.964
- That is the meanest thing
you've ever said to me.

651
00:37:24.064 --> 00:37:26.265
- I know. baby. but it's true.

652
00:37:31.867 --> 00:37:33.867
We can make another.

653
00:37:35.068 --> 00:37:37.069
That way when he leaves.
it won't hurt so bad.

654
00:37:49.793 --> 00:37:52.694
<i>[soft music]</i>

655
00:37:52.794 --> 00:37:59.597
<i>♪ ♪</i>

656
00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:11.401
- Hold on.

657
00:38:14.362 --> 00:38:16.363
1138.

658
00:38:19.004 --> 00:38:21.005
- 1138.

659
00:38:22.005 --> 00:38:23.305
Lost one last year.

660
00:38:23.405 --> 00:38:25.406
Old gal just turned 11.

661
00:38:26.167 --> 00:38:28.167
- Get rid of her.

662
00:38:30.888 --> 00:38:32.949
- [clears throat]

663
00:38:33.049 --> 00:38:34.950
- I needed you at the auction.

664
00:38:35.050 --> 00:38:36.630
- I was at the auction.

665
00:38:36.730 --> 00:38:39.471
- I don't mean checking brands.

666
00:38:39.571 --> 00:38:41.112
- Dad. I stand in bullshit
12 hours a day.

667
00:38:41.212 --> 00:38:42.552
I'm not gonna do it at night.
That's Jamie's job.

668
00:38:42.652 --> 00:38:44.073
- You can't run this place

669
00:38:44.173 --> 00:38:45.674
if you won't interact
with the people. Lee.

670
00:38:45.774 --> 00:38:47.434
- I'm running it right now.
- This ain't running it.

671
00:38:47.534 --> 00:38:48.955
- Don't start with me.
- This ain't running it!

672
00:38:49.055 --> 00:38:52.016
This is working it.

673
00:38:54.417 --> 00:38:55.797
God damn it. 38 years old.

674
00:38:55.897 --> 00:38:57.898
you still don't know
the difference.

675
00:39:03.020 --> 00:39:05.021
- Shit. one's down.

676
00:39:09.102 --> 00:39:12.103
[cows lowing]

677
00:39:40.834 --> 00:39:42.494
- Looks like a breech.

678
00:39:42.594 --> 00:39:45.415
- Can we get her up?
- No. we'll pull it--

679
00:39:45.515 --> 00:39:48.937
We'll pull it while she's down.

680
00:39:49.037 --> 00:39:51.037
- You got her?

681
00:39:51.758 --> 00:39:53.578
Okay. ready?

682
00:39:53.678 --> 00:39:54.779
[lowing]

683
00:39:54.879 --> 00:39:56.499
I'm sorry.

684
00:39:56.599 --> 00:39:59.180
[cow huffing]

685
00:39:59.280 --> 00:40:01.501
- You feel the legs?
- Not yet.

686
00:40:01.601 --> 00:40:03.102
[cow grunts]

687
00:40:03.202 --> 00:40:05.583
- Easy. mama. Easy. easy.

688
00:40:05.683 --> 00:40:07.683
- Okay. got them. I got them.
All right. tell me when.

689
00:40:09.444 --> 00:40:13.025
[straining] Tell me when.
[cow moaning]

690
00:40:13.125 --> 00:40:14.746
- All right. go.
- [grunts]

691
00:40:14.846 --> 00:40:17.227
- Shh. easy. mama.

692
00:40:17.327 --> 00:40:18.347
Shh.

693
00:40:18.447 --> 00:40:20.268
- [grunting]

694
00:40:20.368 --> 00:40:23.509
[lowing]

695
00:40:23.609 --> 00:40:27.931
[both cows lowing]

696
00:40:43.696 --> 00:40:46.357
- [sighs. laughs]

697
00:40:46.457 --> 00:40:48.458
- [sighs. groans]

698
00:40:51.539 --> 00:40:53.540
- Whew.

699
00:40:59.382 --> 00:41:01.663
- When you look at that calf.
what do you see?

700
00:41:05.584 --> 00:41:07.485
- I see a life
I got to feed and defend

701
00:41:07.585 --> 00:41:09.786
until it grows up and feeds me.

702
00:41:13.347 --> 00:41:15.348
- That's what
a cowboy should see.

703
00:41:18.469 --> 00:41:20.970
But a cattleman sees
a $293 investment

704
00:41:21.070 --> 00:41:24.932
worth $1.100 in seven months

705
00:41:25.032 --> 00:41:27.032
whether it feeds anyone or not.

706
00:41:29.073 --> 00:41:32.154
- Wish I saw it
different. Dad.

707
00:41:35.675 --> 00:41:38.036
- Well. we see it
the way we see it. son.

708
00:41:40.877 --> 00:41:43.838
[cattle lowing]

709
00:42:06.647 --> 00:42:09.388
- Well. if it isn't
bachelor number two

710
00:42:09.488 --> 00:42:12.909
up at the crack of 9:30
and dressed to seize the day.

711
00:42:13.009 --> 00:42:14.710
- Yeah.

712
00:42:14.810 --> 00:42:16.630
It's Saturday.
- No weekends on a ranch.

713
00:42:16.730 --> 00:42:19.471
You know that.

714
00:42:19.571 --> 00:42:21.072
- Nice to see
you're still smoking.

715
00:42:21.172 --> 00:42:23.173
- [laughs]

716
00:42:23.733 --> 00:42:26.674
Well. women in this family
don't live much past 40 anyway.

717
00:42:26.774 --> 00:42:30.035
so I might as well
enjoy my time.

718
00:42:30.135 --> 00:42:32.176
- What are you doing here?

719
00:42:34.497 --> 00:42:36.497
- Same thing I always do.

720
00:42:37.738 --> 00:42:39.739
Fixing something you couldn't.

721
00:42:41.019 --> 00:42:43.020
You missed breakfast.
[door opens and closes]

722
00:42:49.382 --> 00:42:51.383
[buffalo grunting]

723
00:42:55.945 --> 00:42:58.085
- Now. what the hell are we
supposed to do with buffalo?

724
00:42:58.185 --> 00:43:00.186
- You'll see.

725
00:43:00.826 --> 00:43:02.807
- Yeah. well how much
these sumbitches cost?

726
00:43:02.907 --> 00:43:04.908
- Well. they ain't cheap.

727
00:43:25.755 --> 00:43:28.116
[horse whinnies]

728
00:43:35.159 --> 00:43:37.140
I was thinking
about you yesterday.

729
00:43:37.240 --> 00:43:38.900
A friend of mine
in Jackson Hole

730
00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:40.941
was talking about their rodeo.

731
00:43:41.041 --> 00:43:43.582
Bozeman doesn't have one.
Why not?

732
00:43:43.682 --> 00:43:45.663
- It's 'cause nobody here
cares about rodeos.

733
00:43:45.763 --> 00:43:47.503
- Oh. you're wrong. John.

734
00:43:47.603 --> 00:43:50.825
Every millionaire I know
wants to be a cowboy.

735
00:43:50.925 --> 00:43:53.666
Authenticity's the one thing
that money can't buy.

736
00:43:53.766 --> 00:43:55.186
It'd be good for Bozeman

737
00:43:55.286 --> 00:43:57.947
and a great way
to honor men like you.

738
00:43:58.047 --> 00:43:59.748
- Yeah. well. parading us
in front of your friends.

739
00:43:59.848 --> 00:44:03.829
Dan. isn't an honor.
It's a--it's an insult.

740
00:44:03.929 --> 00:44:05.830
You want to build subdivisions.

741
00:44:05.930 --> 00:44:07.931
move to Dallas.
I won't have them here.

742
00:44:09.931 --> 00:44:11.952
Yeah. that's right.
Nothing happens in this valley

743
00:44:12.052 --> 00:44:14.793
I don't know about.

744
00:44:14.893 --> 00:44:16.874
- It's called progress. John.

745
00:44:16.974 --> 00:44:19.195
and progress doesn't need
your permission.

746
00:44:19.295 --> 00:44:22.276
- Yeah. in this valley it does.

747
00:44:22.376 --> 00:44:24.077
- What do you care
what I build?

748
00:44:24.177 --> 00:44:25.757
You expect me to believe
that you're concerned

749
00:44:25.857 --> 00:44:27.918
about the environment?

750
00:44:28.018 --> 00:44:30.839
You raise cattle.
you fucking hypocrite.

751
00:44:30.939 --> 00:44:33.360
You know what I think it is?
I think it's ego.

752
00:44:33.460 --> 00:44:35.281
I think it chaps your ass

753
00:44:35.381 --> 00:44:37.041
to walk through a grocery store
and nobody knows who you are.

754
00:44:37.141 --> 00:44:38.442
- You bet your ass it does

755
00:44:38.542 --> 00:44:40.763
because every family
you move in

756
00:44:40.863 --> 00:44:42.283
moves a family I know out.

757
00:44:42.383 --> 00:44:44.044
- With every winner.
there's a loser.

758
00:44:44.144 --> 00:44:46.525
- First thing you said
I agree with.

759
00:44:46.625 --> 00:44:48.445
- Can't stop it. John.

760
00:44:48.545 --> 00:44:50.526
- Watch me.

761
00:44:50.626 --> 00:44:52.767
- Go ahead. say it.

762
00:44:52.867 --> 00:44:54.928
It'll make a lawsuit
much simpler.

763
00:44:55.028 --> 00:44:56.368
